the detroit news and the detroit free press will 
increase the price of their daily papers to 25 cents from 15 cents 
and 20 cents respectively the newspapers announced tuesday 
the increases had been anticipated since the newspapers began a 
partial merger nov 27 advertisers also will begin paying higher 
rates sunday because of the joint operating agreement 
the newspapers are merging business advertising production and 
circulation operations to cut costs while keeping separate news and 
editorial departments 
the free press remains a morning newspaper weekdays the news 
will have one morning edition available for street sales only and 
three editions for afternoon home delivery there will be joint 
weekend editions under the masthead of the detroit news and free 
press 
the price for the sunday edition will go up to 1 from 75 cents 
this sunday 
robert j hall publisher and chairman of the free press said 
he hopes the newspapers the ninth and 10thlargest in the 
country will maintain their circulation 
home subscription rates will remain unchanged at least through 
december said william j keating president and chief executive 
officer of the detroit newspaper agency which handles business and 
publishing matters for the newspapers 
wednesdays edition of the free press said the dna had begun 
telling advertisers of its new rates but company officials 
declined to disclose the size of the increase 
the joa first requested in 1986 was approved by thenattorney 
general edwin meese in 1988 but stalled by court challenges from a 
coalition of readers and advertisers legal delays ended nov 13 
when the us supreme courts 44 tie on an appeal let stand lower 
court rulings upholding the agreement 
