<DOCNO> AP891206-0019 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal health officials say laboratory 
findings that very high doses of the antiaids drug azt cause 
tumors in aging laboratory rodents should cause little concern for 
people with aids 
dr james mason the top health official at the department of 
health and human services said that while the results are 
significant they do not show azt causes cancer in humans 
the public health service still strongly recommends that aids 
patients continue their zidovudine azt therapy under 
consultation with their physicians mason said tuesday 
dan hoth director of the aids division at the national 
institute of allergy and infectious diseases noted in the study 
conducted by the maker of azt burroughs wellcome co the rodents 
received much higher doses of azt for a much longer time than aids 
patients do 
we know that azt prolongs life in humans with aids he 
said when you compare that known benefit of azt to the 
theoretical risk of tumors the only right thing to do is to 
continue using azt 
azt is the only drug approved by the food and drug 
administration that attacks the aids virus directly it was 
approved in march 1987 
more than 40000 aids patients take azt in the united states no 
one is known to have recovered from aids 
burroughs wellcome co sent notice to physicians informing them 
of the studys findings that some of the rats and mice that 
received very high doses of azt for most of their normal life spans 
developed vaginal tumors at the end of their lives 
the results the company said are of limited predictive value 
for humans 
though the results raise the possibility of a carcinogenic 
potential in general they should not be interpreted as applying 
only to the vagina or to women said company spokeswoman kathy 
bartlett 
the company said in its study that high doses of azt were given 
to 360 female rats and mice for about 22 months almost their 
entire normal life span the test rodents were divided into three 
groups and each given different doses of the drug 
of the 120 receiving the highest dose seven developed cancerous 
vaginal tumors and two had benign vaginal tumors burroughs 
wellcome said one benign tumor was found in the group receiving 
the middle dose while no treatmentrelated tumors were seen at the 
lowest dose the company said 
the company said no treatmentrelated tumors were observed in an 
equal number of male rodents 
tumors in rodents were observed on laboratory examination 
toward the end of their lifespan and only in animals which had 
received very high doses of zidovudine said the company based 
in research triangle park nc 
burroughs wellcomes studies were part of routine tests that are 
carried out on new drugs and take about three years to conduct the 
company said 
</TEXT>
