<TEXT>
pope john paul ii says the ecological crisis 
is becoming a threat to world peace and can only be solved by 
overcoming greed consumerism and indifference to life 
in his annual message for the roman catholic churchs world day 
of peace the pope said tuesday that the destruction of the 
environment is actually a moral issue 
the pope said he wasnt asking that the modern world return to a 
paradise lost but for moderation discipline and the spirit of 
sacrifice 
threats to world peace he said come not only from the arms 
race regional conflicts and social injustice but also the 
plundering of natural resources and by a progressive decline in the 
quality of life 
the sense of precariousness and insecurity that such a 
situation engenders is a seabed for collective selfishness 
disregard for others and dishonesty john paul said in the 
message which is sent to world leaders 
the pope chooses a different topic each year for the new years 
message and used it to present some of his widest views to date on 
the environment last year he examined threats to peace from 
ethnic disputes 
john paul spared neither industrialized nor developing societies 
from criticism 
it is manifestly unjust that a privileged few should continue 
to accumulate excess goods squandering available resources while 
masses of people are living in conditions of misery at the very 
lowest level of subsistence the pope said 
but he said countries in the process of industrialization are 
not morally free to repeat the errors made in the past by others 
and recklessly continue to damage the environment through 
industrial pollutants radical deforestration or unlimited 
exploitation of nonrenewable resources 
john paul did not name any individual country at a news 
conference to present the message a vatican official monsignor 
jorge maria mejia noted that the church in italy the philippines 
brazil and indonesia has spoken out against destruction of forests 
the pope condemned genetic manipulation the unscrupulous 
development of new forms of plant and animal life and 
unacceptable experimentation on the origins of human life 
he lamented that laboratory tests continue on new offensive 
weapons capable of altering the balance of nature despite 
international agreements prohibiting chemical bacteriological and 
biological warfare 
the seriousness of the ecological crisis he said lays bare 
the depth of mans moral crisis if an appreciation of the value of 
the human person and of human life is lacking we will also lose 
interest in others and the earth itself 
