us district judge james o ellison ordered the lawyers jailed 
for contempt hours later after an emergency session the us 
circuit court in denver stayed the contempt citations and ordered 
the men freed on their own recognizance until an appeal could be 
heard 
the men claim fee information is a privileged communication 
between attorney and client ellison disagreed 
the attorneyclient privilege shields only those 
communications made for the purpose of securing legal advice 
ellison wrote in the court order matters involving the payment 
of fees and the identity of clients are not generally privileged 
the federal government is investigating dallas nightclub owner 
james coltharps alleged connection to the methamphetamine lab in 
beggs about 30 miles south of tulsa federal prosecutors allege 
coltharp may have paid the attorneys fees for the convicted lab 
crew 
the lawyers are stanley monroe and john echols of tulsa and 
scott anderson james walker and tex mcconathy of dallas none is 
accused of any impropriety and none is the target of the grand jury 
inquiry us attorney tony m graham said 
in his court order ellison said the fact that the men are not 
the target of the investigation means they cannot claim protection 
under the fifth amendment 
nothing in the circumstances before this court demonstrates 
that compliance with the subpoenas as to the payment of fees 
would in any way convey the substance of any confidential 
communication ellison wrote 
</TEXT>
