<TEXT>
for the opposition the 18day 
popular revolt that has brought their compatriots a heady dose of 
freedom has been a harrowing round of endless meetings to make sure 
the uprising stays on course 
vaclav havel the oppositions bestknown leader looked 
exhausted wednesday when he announced that a new government would 
be formed with opposition approval later this week 
bustling around the oppositions new headquarters in a central 
prague gallery grabbing sandwiches and coffee the activists are 
growing more weary with each day that brings them a real say in 
czechoslovakias politics 
dissidents who once spent hours talking to reporters in their 
apartments bustled in and out of a tactical session pausing only 
to smile and refusing to answer questions 
stanislaw milota a film director banned from his profession for 
years organized the oppositions own cameras to transmit havels 
news conference 
it will be good when this war is over he sighed the rings 
under his eyes dark from lack of sleep 
we are tired people here said a weary john bok almost 
frantic in his appeal for calm we have been sleeping only one 
and a half hours so be patient please 
in the 18 astounding days that have propelled the charter 77 
dissidents who make up the core of civic forum from isolation to 
daily negotiations with the communists tactics have changed almost 
hourly 
at its founding meeting nov 19 civic forum simply demanded the 
ouster of five hardline communists associated with the crackdown 
after 1968 two men linked to nov 17 police brutality and an 
investigation into that crackdown threatening a general strike if 
those demands were not met 
when more than 100000 people turned out in prague to support 
them the next day the opposition found itself suddenly wielding 
surprising force 
on nov 21 there was a first meeting with communist premier 
ladislav adamec at two marathon sessions nov 24 and nov 26 the 
communist party ousted the leaders who had pursued hardline 
policies for 21 years 
on nov 28 the day after the hugely successful general strike 
adamec relinquished the communists 41year hold on power voted 
out of the constitution the next day in parliament 
all the time the opposition was changing tactics formulating 
new demands intended to ensure that this time czechoslovakia gets 
real democracy and not the communistled reforms crushed by a 
warsaw pact invasion in 1968 
within days of civic forums formation havel and other 
dissidents who spent years in jail and isolation from society had 
assembled a team of economists lawyers and other advisers many of 
them experts who spent years in the wilderness after the crackdown 
on the 1968 prague spring 
changing roles swiftly from dissident playwright to political 
negotiator havel has closeted himself with these advisers to 
hammer out tactics 
as the protest spread to workers more representatives from the 
factories were admitted to these sessions and addressed opposition 
rallies 
the composition of delegations visiting adamec and other 
officials also has changed to reflect new strands in the movement 
bringing in slovak representatives students young people and 
artists 
its really funny said an opposition activist who did not 
want to be identified everybody wants to meet with us now to 
prove how democratic they are and how they always favored reform 
the higher the stakes the more the opposition has taken on the 
attributes of any political organization dealing with a public avid 
for news leaks are constantly sought and rarely given leading 
figures who spoke publicly on any point days ago have clammed up 
please understand that we cannot answer any of the questions 
you want to ask us said spokesman jiri dienstbier after havel 
announced a new government would be formed this week these are 
crazy times really crazy 
another problem some activists face is that they still have jobs 
amid their opposition activity 
dienstbier and fellow dissident petr uhl for instance swap 
shifts as stokers at the same factory their fellow workers cant 
make up for them all the time 
last week i had the wives of coworkers sending me notes as 
we held our meetings offering to work extra dienstbier said 
with a chuckle 
the success of what is halfjokingly known as the velvet 
revolution for its smoothness depends on the ability of the 
opposition to keep the ball rolling 
on tuesday constitutional lawyers who had a blueprint for a 
new democratic constitution ready for months presented it on 
behalf of civic forum to parliament 
by wednesday the opposition had new demands to remove the 
federal and czech regional public prosecutors 
keeping the pressure up in this way involves the help of legions 
of young people working as guards and secretaries and running 
errands 
they bustle around the new opposition headquarters hurriedly 
relocated tuesday to a downtown club from the nearby laterna magika 
theater 
there is almost no time to keep up with events absorbing 
everyday life economist vaclav klaus a leading adviser to civic 
forum pounced on a pile of newspapers lying around the offices 
wednesday 
i havent seen the newspapers for days he said smiling as 
he plunged into another closeddoor meeting 
</TEXT>
