<TEXT>
the national transportation safety board today 
blamed the crew of a montana rail link freight train for failing to 
secure the brakes before a crash and chemical explosion that forced 
evacuation of 2000 people in subfreezing helena last winter 
the board also cited as contributing to the accident the 
decision of an engineer to rearrange the trains locomotives while 
leaving the cars unattended on a mountain grade the effects of the 
cold that reached a windchill factor of minus70 degrees at the 
time of the feb 2 crash and inadequate training by the railroad 
management 
the board voting 40 issued several recommendations to the 
railroad to burlington northern railroad which owned the tracks 
the federal railraod administration the association of american 
railroads and the city of helena 
the independent safety board determines probable cause of 
accidents and makes recommendations for improving safety but has no 
statutory or police authority 
cars from the train which had been making its way up a long 
mountain grade en route to spokane wash coasted backwards nine 
miles into helena and hit another train and a propane tank flames 
from the propane explosion ignited one of the derailed cars which 
contained highly flammable chemical 
the ntsb noted that the release of hazardous materials 
contributed to the severity of the 448 am crash in which no one 
was killed or seriously injured damage was estimated at 6 
million not including several private homes that suffered broken 
windows and other damage 
board investigators said the crew of the train failed to 
properly secure train brakes after disconnecting cars so they could 
rearrange engines that were helping the train up the long grade 
toward the continental divide 
the decision to move the engines was made after the heater and 
then the engine failed in the lead locomotive 
</TEXT>
