<TEXT>
house republican leader bob michel said 
wednesday that television reporting on congress takes second 
place to reporting on the president and few newspapers provide 
detailed reporting of house and senate proceedings 
michel spoke at a national press club luncheon during a 
symposium on the press and a divided government sponsored by 
the gerald r ford library and the national press foundation 
former president ford also discussed the subject of press 
coverage of a government in which republicans control the white 
house and democrats dominate in congress 
i dont think its hard ford said all you have to do is 
be fair 
michel said to oversimplify the issue for the sake of debate 
lets say television with its emphasis on the personal has become 
the major presidential news medium and print with its ability to 
describe complex issues has become the major congressional medium 
for tv evening news with its mass audience television 
reporting on congress takes second place to reporting on the 
president he said 
the only time network television gives the congress a detailed 
look is when scandal erupts or if some committee is holding 
hearings on some currently hot topic michel said the rest of 
the time we could just as well be on the moon so far as the mass 
audience is concerned 
the illinois republican told his audience print journalism 
offers a bit more opportunity to go into detail but how many 
american newspapers give congress indepth coverage not many 
aggressive press coverage of strongly held clashing values in 
a divided government would be good for america michel said 
but we dont have that kind of coverage the press in general 
does a good job reporting on the foibles and the gaffes and the 
slips of a president but it doesnt provide a mass audience with 
the underlying realities of democratic control of the house 
michel said that recently he and rep mickey edwards rokla 
held a news conference on the issue of house reform and added 
after we spoke the first question and most of the rest 
concerned a thenprominent house scandal only one major newspaper 
reported our proposals for reform 
im not saying scandals shouldnt be covered michel said 
all im saying is that the dull workaday routine of the house 
that affects 200 million americans deserves equal time 
so today i offer the networks and the majority of our nations 
newspapers a challenge prove that im wrong 
</TEXT>
