a nuclear power plant worker says he feels 
vindicated by a ruling that a utility discriminated against him by 
firing him after he voiced safety concerns about the project 
the labor department ordered arizona public service co to 
rehire william david simmons and give him back pay the utility 
operates and partly owns the palo verde nuclear generating station 
50 miles west of phoenix 
simmons 33 was fired oct 12 after being accused of cheating 
on a training test required by palo verde however the labor 
department said the utility couldnt substantiate the allegations 
simmons did not cheat on the exam and has been subjected to 
discrimination by the employer the department wrote in a nov 7 
letter to the utility and to simmons attorney stephen kohn 
kohn said simmons earned about 100000 a year as a 
radioactivewaste technician simmons hasnt been rehired and 
remains unemployed kohn told the associated press on wednesday 
simmons who had worked at palo verde since 1982 said the 
finding was a relief 
they attempted to destroy me and my lifestyle and now i feel 
vindicated he saidive never been known as a liar or a 
cheater this feels good i can tell you that 
don andrews a palo verde spokesman said wednesday he couldnt 
comment on the labor department ruling because it was a personnel 
matter and any actions of the case are still in progress 
andrews declined to say whether the ruling would be appealed 
however kohn said the utility had appealed it and a jan 9 
hearing on the matter has been scheduled before a department of 
labor judge in washington 
a federal nuclear regulatory commission spokesman said the 
agency was aware of the case and would ask aps for its account of 
the incident 
according to the labor department investigators report simmons 
was disliked by management for complaining to plant operators and 
regulators about his safety concerns 
complaints included potential problems with sodium hydroxide 
that reportedly was leaking into the surrounding water table and 
that employees werent qualified to use respirators 
simmons originally was faulted because he didnt attend required 
training classes but the labor department said plant managers 
never scheduled simmons to attend the classes 
eventually simmons was required to take the exams without 
attending the training classes investigator william whitfield 
reported during one of those exams palo verde officials said four 
instructors watched simmons look at small yellow notes 
however the utility was unable to prove that simmons had used 
the notes for a test considered to be so easy that no one could 
think of a reason for cheating whitfield wrote 
simmons acknowledged he brought study notes into the exam with 
him but said he didnt use them 
