<TEXT>
mexicos commercial bank creditors have 
committed about 90 percent of a financing package for 19891992 
covering about 48 billion of mexican medium and longterm debt 
according to an official announcement 
the remaining commitments are expected by the end of this week 
mexican finance undersecretary angel gurria and bank representative 
william r rhodes said in a joint communique tuesday 
rhodes is cochairman of a 15member bank committee that reached 
a preliminary agreement with mexico last july and recommended its 
approval to mexicos approximately 400 creditor banks 
to date 345 banks have committed to the package the communique 
said only two banks with small exposure have so far declined to 
participate 
we are getting positive responses from some banks that havent 
participated in the process for a number of years rhodes said 
banks commitments to the three options in the package are 
following the pattern anticipated by rhodes at a press conference 
nov 14 new money is running between 8 percent and 10 percent of 
the total committed the remainder is split about evenly between 
repackaged debt in which either the principal or interest has been 
reduced the announcement said 
the communique said the signing of the agreements is expected to 
start before the end of december assuming continuing rapid 
progress in completing the complex legal documentation 
the package covers nearly half of mexicos total 107 billion 
foreign debt second in the developing world to the 120 billion 
owed by brazil 
the package represents the first significant reduction in a 
third world governments debt to international commercial banks it 
is considered an important step in the third world debt crisis that 
began seven years ago when mexico announced in august 1982 it was 
unable to meet obligations 
since then third world debt has grown to about 13 trillion 
the agreement has also been seen as a test of the bush 
administrations policy for reducing third world debt and as a 
milestone for other countries waiting to renegotiate 
under the agreement the creditor banks have three options a 35 
percent reduction in principal reduction of the interest rate on 
loans to 625 percent from around 10 percent previously or 
providing new loans equal to 25 percent of what mexico owes the 
bank 
</TEXT>
