defense lawyers in the gaf corp stock 
manipulation trial have introduced newly obtained telephone records 
that appear to contradict pivotal government testimony about calls 
discussing the alleged fraud 
gaf attorney arthur liman called the records which previously 
were thought to be nonexistent obviously very crucial 
extraordinary 
the new evidence indicates no calls were placed on longdistance 
wats lines from the jefferies amp co brokerage to gaf or its vice 
chairman james t sherwin during times in october 1986 when the 
government alleges the manipulation was discussed 
the defense rested its case tuesday after actress liv ullman 
testified on sherwins behalf as the final witness in the 
sevenweek criminal trial in manhattan federal court 
gaf two subsidiaries and sherwin are charged with allegedly 
trying to boost union carbide corps share price in 1986 shortly 
before selling a large block of the stock after a failed takeover 
bid they also were charged with securities fraud wire fraud and 
conspiracy 
the case is in its third trial after two mistrials earlier this 
year 
jefferies amp co trading director james t melton has testified 
he called sherwin between 430 pm and 5 pm on oct 29 30 and 
31 in 1986 shortly after the pacific stock exchange closed to 
discuss actions taken those days to close the stock above 22 a 
share as allegedly ordered by sherwin 
other calls to sherwin to discuss the scheme allegedly were made 
while he was at his doctors office and at standard amp poors corp 
but american telephone amp telegraph co records introduced monday 
indicate that no calls were made during the half hour in question 
on any of jefferies amp cos 15 wats lines to gaf or sherwin or to 
the other offices 
liman said the records contradicted testimony by melton and his 
trading assistant maureen oconnor who said melton called sherwin 
within moments of the markets close 
defense lawyers said privately they believe the new information 
shows that the calls to sherwin never were made no records of the 
calls appeared on jefferies amp cos regular longdistance telephone 
bills either 
the defense called an atampt supervisor who retrieved the records 
and a private investigator who analyzed them on the witness stand 
assistant us attorney carl h loewenson jr did not attempt to 
rebut the testimony 
the purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize 
profits after a failed takeover attempt by wayne njbased gaf of 
much larger union carbide gaf a specialty chemicals company held 
10 million shares of union carbide after the failed bid and sold 5 
million in november 1986 for 23 a share 
