<TEXT>
employees in honeywell incs washington 
area office were pressured by their supervisors in the late 1970s 
and early 1980s to obtain secret budget documents from the 
pentagon a federal court jury was told today 
retired honeywell employee frank lozito testified that among 
those he received documents from was former boeing co worker 
richard lee fowler who is on trial on charges of illegally 
obtaining budget documents from the pentagon 
folwer has pleaded innocent to 39 counts including conspiracy 
illegal conveyance of classfied documents and mail fraud boeing 
has pleaded guilty to receiving classified documents and has agreed 
to pay a 52 million fine 
lozito said he was asked by his supervisor to get classified air 
force budget documents and turned to fowler an old friend for 
help 
honeywell worked on a managementbyobjective system lozito 
said of his minneapolisbased employer 
lozito said one of his objectives was to establish meaningful 
contacts with the air force and that meant getting classified 
documents containing budget information the pentagon used to plan 
its spending 
such material could help defense contractors such as boeing and 
honeywell in bidding for defense projects by giving them inside 
information on what the pentagon would want 
lozito said he got documents from fowler five or 10 times a 
year from 1979 to early 1984 
fowler often passed him documents on the street outside boeings 
arlington va office lozito said adding that he copied the 
documents and returned the originals to fowler 
donna fountain a senior security administrator for honeywell 
testified that in the early 1980s she was ordered to keep a 
separate log of classified documents that lozito and others brought 
into the honeywell office 
the log was kept in a separate case that was not available 
to defense investigative service inspectors who worked for the 
pentagon she said 
ms fountain said the documents were kept in the personal safes 
of the employees involved and were removed from honeywell offices 
before such inspections 
i thought it was part of the old boy network friends helping 
friends ms fountain said i believed it was quite widespread 
in the industry 
both ms fountain and lozito testified with guaranteed immunity 
from prosecution by us attorneys 
fowlers attorneys have said their client was hired specifically 
to get the documents for boeing they were readily available to 
defense contractors rules covering their release were unclear and 
charges were filed against him only after he refused to tell 
defense investigative services inspectors who gave him the 
documents 
fowler worked for boeing from 1979 until he was fired in 1986 
three former boeing security employees testified tuesday that 
classified material was logged at the seattlebased aerospace 
companys office in the washington suburb of arlington 
they said pentagon inspectors never raised questions about the 
documents listed in the logs 
deborah null who was a clerk at the arlington office from 1978 
to 1984 testified that inspectors reviewed boeings classified 
record log twice a year and the log included specific references to 
the documents fowler is accused of obtaining illegally 
ms null also said that even though military rules required that 
she have receipts from the pentagon before entering the documents 
in the log dis officials and boeing employees including fowler 
said it was no problem if she didnt 
</TEXT>
