allegheny international inc said wednesday a 
federal judge has approved a 625 million settlement of 
shareholders lawsuits from 1986 that accused some officers and 
directors of violating securities laws 
the settlement of derivative and classaction lawsuits will be 
funded by the officers and directors liability insurance of 
allegheny international the pittsburghbased small appliance 
manufacturer will not be required to spend any of its own money to 
satisfy claims 
under terms of the settlement approved by us district judge 
gustave diamond the company will receive 1 million decatur 
income fund inc will receive 337428 to settle its claim and all 
legal expenses and legal fees will be deducted from the gross 
amount 
the rest of the fund will be divided among investors who bought 
allegheny international common stock preferred stock and 
subordinated debentures between aug 1 1985 and april 18 1986 
class members are eligible to receive compensation if they have 
not excluded themselves from the class and file timely proofs of 
claims 
unsecured creditors meanwhile have filed a competing 
reorganization plan in us bankruptcy court for the financially 
troubled company 
the plan marks the first time any group other than the company 
has filed a reorganization plan since allegheny international lost 
its exclusive right to do so in june 
allegheny international has operated under chapter 11 of us 
bankruptcy laws for almost two years during that time the company 
proposed nine reorganization plans the latest of which was 
submitted last week 
the proposal does not specify whether assets should be sold 
although the unsecured creditors previously have called for the 
sale of the companys flagship ostersunbeam small appliance unit 
like the companys most recent proposal the creditors plan 
would repay most of allegheny internationals 740 million in debts 
with new stock its plan would issue virtually no cash to anyone 
other than trade creditors however while the companys plan would 
distribute 200 million in cash most of it to bank lenders 
those lenders would get only notes and stock under the unsecured 
creditors proposal 
unsecured creditors would become the companys majority 
stockholders and gain the right to name most directors most 
creditors would get between 48 and 755 shares of common stock in 
the reorganized company for each 1000 they are owed 
current shareholders would get only 15 percent of the 
reorganized companys shares the same as envisioned in the 
companys plan 
