<TEXT>
warren e buffett extended his 
stockpicking prowess to champion international corp on wednesday 
as his berkshire hathaway inc bought 300000 shares of preferred 
stock for 300 million 
berkshire bought a new series of convertible stock that gives 
the omaha nebbased company about 8 percent of shareholders 
voting rights in champion a paper products company with 51 
billion in sales last year 
berkshire will have voting rights with the preferred stock 
because thats how its negotiated said champion spokesman 
robert w turner 
we are delighted to place this issue with a longterm investor 
who has such an outstanding reputation said andrew c sigler 
champions chairman and chief executive officer 
buffett is famous for buying stock in companies that turn out to 
be good longterm investments his picks include salomon brothers 
inc cocacola co gillette co and capital citiesabc inc 
the big thing about buffett is hes in for the long term 
turner said and that has been what our chairman andy sigler 
has been saying for years and years that to be competitive 
worldwide you must make capital investments over the long term 
stamfordbased champion makes paper primarily for copiers 
magazines catalogs and newspapers the company owns 64 million 
acres of timberland in the us and also makes plywood and lumber 
it is a leader in an industry that has enjoyed record profits in 
the last few years but some analysts have predicted a 6month to 
twoyear downturn in the industry because of overcapacity and a 
corresponding drop in prices 
for the three quarters ended sept 30 champion had net income 
of 3294 million on sales of 3896 billion down from a profit of 
3365 million on sales of 3814 billion in the first three 
quarters of 1988 
berkshire had a profit of 2857 million on sales of 2 billion 
last year 
champion issued the shares at 1000 each with each share 
guaranteed a dividend of 925 percent or 9250 per year turner 
said 
the stock is convertible to common stock which can reap higher 
profits but is riskier because it is not guaranteed a dividend 
the board of directors has the authority from time to time to 
issue preference stock as opposed to common stock turner said 
we have not done that very much but its being done on a 
seriesbyseries basis 
he said each preferred share carries about 263 votes or a 
total 75 million votes on all issues submitted to shareholders 
that gives berkshire about 8 percent of the voting rights based on 
91 million to 92 million shares of outstanding common stock 
berkshire agreed to limit its ownership in champion to 18 
percent for the next 10 years unless champions board approves an 
increase berkshire also agreed to certain restrictions on 
reselling the shares 
